message.content:
A breakwater is a man-made structure that is built offshore or along coastlines.
It is designed to protect ships, boats and harbors from the effects of waves and currents.
Breakwaters can be made of concrete, rocks or natural materials such as boulders and gravel.
They are usually built with a sloping front face that absorbs wave energy and dissipates it.
Breakwaters can vary in size and shape, but they typically have a long and narrow profile.
They are most commonly found in busy harbors and ports where there is a high volume of shipping traffic.
The visual characteristics of a breakwater can include a rough and textured surface, with a color that blends into its surroundings.
